data.content:
## What happened

C# 14 introduces new `Span<T>` / `ReadOnlySpan<T>` overload resolution rules. Your `array.Contains(num)` now binds to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** (span-based) instead of **`Enumerable.Contains`** (`IEnumerable<T>`-based). Expression trees can't represent span-based method calls, so this throws at runtime.

## Fix

Force the call to resolve to `Enumerable.Contains` by casting the array to `IEnumerable<int>` or using `.AsEnumerable()`:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Both approaches pin overload resolution to the `IEnumerable<T>` version, which expression trees support. This same pattern applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays (now resolves to the in-place `Span` extension instead of `Enumerable.Reverse`).
